5:52 PM
This is actually a pretty tractable project for someone with your skillset. Let me break down the real difficulty honestly.

Overall: Medium-Hard (but very doable)
The mechanical side is the easiest part you'd think is hard. A rotary axis (basically a turntable/rotary table) + a 3-axis arm gives you 4-axis CNC, which is plenty for a bust. You don't need crazy precision for stone carving — even 0.5mm accuracy looks great on marble because the material is forgiving visually.

Rough architecture:

Rotary axis (A-axis): A beefy stepper/servo + worm gear reduction driving a chuck or faceplate holding the stone block. This is honestly the simplest axis.
3-axis gantry or arm: You could go cartesian gantry (easier, stiffer) or articulated arm (cooler, harder kinematics). For stone, rigidity matters — I'd lean gantry.
Spindle: This is where money goes. You need a real spindle (1-3kW) with diamond or carbide tooling for marble. A trim router won't cut it (pun intended). Budget ~$300-800 for a decent water-cooled spindle.
Frame: Needs to be stiff. Steel or heavy aluminum extrusion. Stone cutting forces are no joke — way higher than wood/plastic CNC.
The actual hard parts:

Rigidity & vibration. This is the #1 failure mode for DIY stone CNC. Marble will punish any flex in your frame with chatter, broken bits, and cracked workpieces. Over-engineer the frame.
Toolpathing / CAM. You need to go from a 3D model of Alexander → 4-axis toolpaths. This is where your agentic coding tools actually shine. You could use something like OpenCAMLib or just generate G-code programmatically. The 4-axis wrapping (rotary + linear) has some nuance but it's well-documented math.
Dust and coolant management. Marble dust is genuinely hazardous (silicosis) and gets everywhere. You basically need a water mist/flood coolant system and serious dust extraction. This is annoying but not technically hard.
Tool wear. Diamond bits wear fast on stone. A full bust might eat through several hundred dollars in tooling. Roughing with aggressive carbide, finishing with diamond.
What I'd actually do if I were you:

Start with a 5th-axis rotary addon to an existing CNC router rather than fully from scratch. Get a Chinese 6040-style CNC frame ($500-1000), beef up the spindle, add a rotary 4th axis ($200-400), and reinforce the frame with steel plates. Then spend your real effort on the software side — generating the toolpaths, tuning feeds/speeds for marble, and iterating.

Going fully from-scratch custom arm is cool but you'll spend 3-4 months just on mechanical debugging before you ever touch stone. The modified-CNC route gets you carving in weeks.

Budget estimate:

Full from scratch: $2,000-4,000 + 2-4 months build time
Modified existing CNC + rotary: $1,000-2,000 + 2-4 weeks
The 3D model of Alexander is the free part — there are excellent public domain photogrammetry scans of classical busts. Or you generate one.

Want me to go deeper on any specific subsystem — the rotary axis design, the CAM/toolpath generation, or the spindle/tooling selection?

