5:55 PM
Yeah that's a totally valid approach. Few reality checks though:

Dremel will work but barely. The problem is torque — a Dremel is like 125W and spins crazy fast but has almost no torque. It'll work for finishing passes on softer stones (soapstone, alabaster, soft marble) but you'll be taking tiny passes forever and burning through bits. A Makita trim router or a cheap 800W water-cooled spindle from AliExpress would be a massive upgrade for like $80-150 more. But honestly, start with the Dremel to prove the concept, then upgrade.

2x2 ft is ambitious for a first go. That's a life-size bust, which means your arm needs like 3+ ft of reach and the forces/vibrations scale up a lot. A 6-8 inch block first would let you validate everything without the structural headaches. Then scale up.

The arm itself — if you're building a proper articulated arm (not gantry), the main thing is gear reduction on every joint. Direct-drive steppers won't have the torque or rigidity for stone. Planetary gearboxes or harmonic drives on each joint. You probably already know this from your robotics background but it's the difference between "works on foam" and "works on marble."

The real magic of your approach is that with agentic coding tools you can probably get the inverse kinematics, motion planning, and G-code interpretation working way faster than most people. That's normally the bottleneck for custom arm CNC — the software is harder than the hardware.

Start with the arm carving foam or wax to validate kinematics, then graduate to soft stone, then marble. You'll get there pretty fast honestly.

