5:56 PM
Yeah 100%, you're basically describing a 6DOF industrial robot arm at that point — which is genuinely the most versatile approach. A 6-axis arm + rotary table gives you full coverage of any surface from any angle, which is exactly how the high-end sculpture robots work (like those Kuka arms that carve for artists).

And you're right that the applications blow open — same arm does CNC milling, welding, pick-and-place, polishing, painting, 3D printing, whatever end effector you slap on it. It's a general purpose manufacturing platform.

The real considerations for from-scratch 6DOF:

Joints 1-3 (base, shoulder, elbow) need to be beefy. These carry the weight of the entire arm plus cutting forces. You're looking at NEMA 34 steppers or servo motors with high-ratio planetary gearboxes (like 50:1 or 100:1). The shoulder joint specifically is the hardest to engineer because it fights gravity constantly under load.

Joints 4-6 (wrist) can be lighter but need precision. This is where harmonic drives shine but they're expensive ($200-500 each). Cycloidal drives are a good DIY alternative — you can CNC or even 3D print them in metal.

The control software is honestly the most interesting part for you. ROS2 + MoveIt for motion planning is the standard path, but given VibeOS and your Rust background you might want to roll your own inverse kinematics and trajectory planning. The math is well-known (Denavit-Hartenberg parameters, Jacobian-based IK) and it's a great problem for agentic tools to help implement.

Biggest trap: people underestimate the arm's weight fighting itself. A 3+ ft reach arm holding a spindle needs counterbalancing or massive motors at the shoulder. Gas springs or counterweights help a lot.

This is a legit project that becomes a platform for everything else. Pretty aligned with your general vibe of building foundational infrastructure.

