Let me think about what "fully custom" actually means here and what the architecture looks like:
The core systems you need:
Rigid body physics engine — this is the foundation. 6DOF articulated body dynamics with joint constraints (revolute joints, gear ratios, torque limits, friction). You don't need a general purpose physics engine — you need articulated body dynamics specifically. Featherstone's algorithm is the gold standard for this, it's O(n) in the number of joints and handles exactly your use case. Implementing it from scratch in Rust is maybe 2-3K lines of core code.
Material removal simulation — this is the hard/cool part. You need to represent the marble block as a volumetric field (SDF or voxel grid) and subtract material where the tool contacts it. At reasonable resolution (0.5mm voxels on a 1ft block) that's ~600x600x600 = ~216M voxels, which is a lot but manageable with sparse representations like octrees. The tool-workpiece intersection is basically a swept volume subtraction each timestep.
Motor/drive simulation — model the closed-loop steppers as torque sources with realistic speed-torque curves, the gearbox ratios and backlash, and the control loop (PID or whatever you end up running). This is what tells you if your motor selection actually works before you buy anything.
Cutting force model — for stone, it's empirical but well-studied. Specific cutting energy for marble is roughly 15-30 N/mm². Given tool engagement geometry from the material removal sim, you get realistic forces fed back into the rigid body dynamics. This closes the loop — forces affect the arm, arm deflection affects the cut.
The renderer — since you want full custom, a real-time Vulkan renderer in Rust with wgpu makes sense. You need mesh extraction from the voxel/SDF field (marching cubes or dual contouring), PBR materials for the marble (subsurface scattering would look incredible), and standard joint visualization for the arm.
Want me to scaffold out the actual project structure and start building this? I'm thinking:
twin/
├── core/           # math primitives, transforms, quaternions
├── physics/        # featherstone dynamics, joint models
├── material/       # voxel field, SDF, material removal
├── cutting/        # force models, tool-workpiece interaction
├── motors/         # stepper models, gearbox, control loops
├── render/         # wgpu renderer, marching cubes, PBR
├── control/        # IK solver, trajectory planner, G-code interp
└── sim/            # main loop, timestep management, state
This is genuinely a several-week project with agentic tools but each module is well-scoped and independently testable. The physics engine alone is a banger portfolio piece. And once it's done you can iterate on arm geometry, motor selection, toolpaths, everything without spending a dollar on hardware.
