Alright let me just give you the kickoff architecture and you can rip:

# Robot Arm Digital Twin — Architecture Spec
**Stack: Rust · wgpu · fully custom physics + renderer**

---

## Day 1: Physics Core + Arm Kinematics

### Rigid Body Dynamics
- Featherstone's Articulated Body Algorithm (ABA) for forward dynamics
- 7 revolute joints (6 arm + 1 rotary table)
- Per-joint: torque limits, viscous friction, coulomb friction, backlash model
- Fixed timestep: 1kHz physics, decoupled from render

### Joint/Motor Model
- Closed-loop stepper model: speed-torque curve (pull-out torque vs RPM)
- Gear reduction: ratio, efficiency, backlash deadband
- PID control loop per joint (position mode)
- Map real BOM components:
  - J1-J3: NEMA 34 12Nm → 100:1 planetary → 1200Nm at joint
  - J4-J6: NEMA 23 3Nm → 50:1 planetary → 150Nm at joint
  - Rotary: NEMA 34 8.5Nm → 80:1 worm → 680Nm

### DH Parameters (approximate)
```
Joint | a (mm) | d (mm) | α (rad) | θ range
------|--------|--------|---------|----------
J1    | 0      | 300    | -π/2   | ±180°
J2    | 500    | 0      | 0      | -45° to +135°
J3    | 400    | 0      | 0      | ±135°
J4    | 0      | 0      | -π/2   | ±180°
J5    | 0      | 300    | π/2    | ±120°
J6    | 0      | 80     | 0      | ±360°
```
Total reach: ~1200mm (~4ft) ✓

### IK Solver
- Damped least squares (Jacobian pseudoinverse) for general IK
- Analytical IK for the spherical wrist (J4-J6) as fast path
- Joint limit clamping + singularity avoidance

---

## Day 2: Material Removal + Cutting Simulation

### Voxel Field
- Sparse octree SDF representation
- Base resolution: 0.5mm → 600³ logical grid for 1ft block
- Octree keeps memory ~50-200MB vs 216M voxels dense
- Operations: subtract swept tool volume per timestep

### Tool Model
- Parameterized tool geometry (ball nose, flat end, tapered)
- Swept volume = tool shape × tool velocity × dt
- Tool wear model: linear wear rate based on cumulative material removed

### Cutting Force Model
- Specific cutting energy: 20 N/mm² (marble baseline)
- Force = specific_energy × chip_area × depth_of_cut
- Chip area from voxel intersection count
- Force vector feeds back into Featherstone dynamics
- Detects: excessive force (tool break), chatter (oscillation), stall (motor torque exceeded)

### Coolant Simulation (visual only)
- Particle system from spindle mount point
- Collision with workpiece SDF for splash
- Purely visual, no thermal modeling needed for v1

---

## Day 3: Renderer + Integration + Toolpath

### wgpu Renderer
- PBR pipeline with metallic-roughness workflow
- Marble material: subsurface scattering approximation (wrap diffuse + translucency)
- Real-time marching cubes mesh extraction from octree SDF
  - Incremental re-mesh only dirty octree nodes (not full rebuild each frame)
- Arm rendered as simple geometric primitives matching real link dimensions
- Shadow mapping, SSAO for depth perception
- Camera: orbit controls, snap to tool-follow, snap to workpiece

### UI / Controls
- Play/pause/step simulation
- Jog individual joints manually
- Load G-code / toolpath file → execute
- Real-time overlay: joint torques, motor temps, cutting force, spindle RPM
- Toggle: wireframe, joint axes, force vectors, tool swept volume

### Toolpath System
- G-code interpreter (G0, G1, G2/G3, rotary A-axis)
- Or: direct toolpath from STL mesh
  - Slice STL into waterline layers
  - Generate zig-zag roughing passes
  - Generate scallop-height finishing passes (ball nose)
  - 4-axis wrapping: map planar toolpath onto rotary surface
- Toolpath preview mode (ghost the full path before running)

---

## Key Data Flow

```
G-code / Toolpath
       ↓
  IK Solver → joint angle targets
       ↓
  PID Control Loop (1kHz)
       ↓
  Motor Model → torque output
       ↓
  Featherstone ABA → joint accelerations → integrate → joint state
       ↓
  Forward Kinematics → tool tip position/orientation
       ↓
  Material Removal (SDF subtract)  ←→  Cutting Force Model
       ↓
  Octree dirty flags → incremental marching cubes
       ↓
  wgpu render (60fps decoupled from physics)
```

---

## Validation Checklist
- [ ] Arm reaches full 1ft block surface from all angles
- [ ] Joint torques stay within motor limits during roughing
- [ ] No singularities in typical carving trajectories
- [ ] Backlash model produces visible surface artifacts (proves it works)
- [ ] Material removal matches expected volume from toolpath
- [ ] Cutting forces within realistic range (50-200N for marble finishing)
- [ ] Frame rate stays >30fps during active carving
- [ ] Can carve Alexander bust from STL start to finish without issues

---

## Stretch Goals
- Vibration / chatter frequency analysis (FFT on force signal)
- Thermal model on motors (predict overheating before it happens)
- Auto-generate optimized toolpaths from mesh (not just replay G-code)
- VR mode (spectate the carving in XR)
- Export final carved SDF as mesh for comparison with target STL

That's your full spec. Honestly the hardest single piece is the incremental marching cubes on the octree SDF — everything else is either well-known algorithms or straightforward engineering. And if you nail this, you literally have a digital twin platform that generalizes to any robot arm + any subtractive manufacturing process.
